commit_message:
avoid deadlock on osfstorage quotas w/ large files  * Exhaust stream before throwing a 507 Storage Quota Exceeded error
   when uploading to osfstorage.  If the error is thrown before the
   stream is exhausted, there is a possibility that the streamreader
   will `await` forever expecting more data to come in.  This is bad
   b/c a user uploading a moderately-sized file (~20Mb or greater)
   will see their upload hang w/o getting useful context as to why.

   With this change, a user uploading a medium-to-large file (~20Mb -
   ~1Gb) will get a relevant error message after a long wait.  A user
   uploading a *very* large file (~1Gb+) might still get an ambiguous
   error.

   This is an ugly and disgusting hack.  It would be *much* better to
   abort the reading/writing of the upload stream so we don't have to
   read the entirety of a large file, but I haven't figured out to
   stop it w/o causing unrecoverable errors.

 [ENG-2346]

Add toggles for keen event logging  * Add three new switches/envvars to manage keen logging:

   * `KEEN_ENABLE_LOGGING` will turn on/off *all* keen logging

   * `KEEN_PRIVATE_LOG_ACTIONS` will set logging for actions to the
     private collection

   * `KEEN_PUBLIC_LOG_ACTIONS` will set logging for actions to the
     public collection

validate osfstorage caps when moving between all nodes  * Slight change in spec: move/copy actions between different projects
   within the same region should verify that the destination has not
   exceeded its cap.

add retry support to quota checks  * Retry osfstorage limit checks a configurable number of times.

   OSF calculates quota limits asynchronously.  If the limit check is
   still being calculated, OSF will return a 202.  This calculation is
   expected to be fast, so allow up to two retries before falling back
   to the default response.  For the initial implementation of storage
   caps, the default is to allow uploads.

check osfstorage quotas on uploads and some movecopies  * When uploading, moving, or copying to osfstorage, verify that the
   destination is not already over its alloted quota.  Moving/copying
   between two osfstorages in the same region is a simple metadata
   update, does not use up any additional space, and is therefore
   exempt from quota checking.  Moving/copying across storage regions
   uses space on the destination region and *is* subject to quota
   enforcement.

 * Update existing upload/move/copy tests to intercept and mock
   quota-checking tests.

 * Add new tests to verify that upload/move/copy requests to
   over-quota projects are properly rejected.

 [ENG-2249]

update wb v1 auth payload to include intention  * When requesting auth from the OSF, WB includes metadata about the
   requested action.  This metadata had been overloaded to mean both
   "what is the user trying to do" and "what permissions does the user
   need to do it".  In the past it was easy to infer the latter from
   the former, but with the addition of osfstorage quotas, that is no
   longer the case.  The overloading also made it very confusing to
   reason about both the OSF and WB sides of this request.  Factor out
   this code into a new method, `_determine_actions`, and update the
   auth payload to include the intent separate from the permissions.

 * Update v1's movecopy to pass `path` to the auth object's `fetch`
   method.  Everyone else does it, why shouldn't they?

 * Update tests for new permissions & intent fields.

 [ENG-2249]

Bump sentry-sdk dep version to avoid high mem usage  * sentry-sdk's changelog[1] for v0.14.1 includes a fix to avoid high
   memory usage when issuing lots of errors.  Bump WB's dep to take
   advantage.

 [1] https://github.com/getsentry/sentry-python/blob/master/CHANGES.md

set higher timeout for aiohttp get/put/post requests  * Set a default timeout limit of one hour (3600s) for aiohttp
   GET/PUT/POST requests.  After the release of OATHPIT, some users were
   reporting that large file uploads and downloads were failing on
   slower connections.  The aiohttp upgrade added an implicit
   five-minute timeout that was cutting off transmissions between WB
   and the upstream provider.

   The default is set to be generous with the expectation that a proxy
   between the user and WB will be responsible for killing requests
   that are taking too long.  The default can be overridden by setting
   the `AIOHTTP_TIMEOUT` envvar.

fix some gitlab downloads  * Fetch the download size from the `X-Gitlab-Size` header instead of
   relying on `Content-Length`.  The default behavior of
   ResponseStreamReader is to get the expected response size from the
   response's C-L header, but not all GL downloads provide that.  The
   X-G-S does appear to be standard, so rely on that instead.

 * Side-effect: the Range header is no longer supported on GL
   downloads.  It had been implemented by manually slurping the
   contents into memory and slicing out the requested bytes.  The new
   endpoint does not support the Range header.

fix unused var lints in tests found by sonarqube  * Remove lots of `with pytest.raises() as exc:` where `exc` was never
   tested.

 * Don't save unused return values or try to save them when the method
   is expected to raise an exception.

fix duplicate test issues found by sonarqube  * Fix some tests that were copy-n-pastes of other tests but were
   never updated to be distinct.

 * Fix a test that failed to assert() its result.

Improve async_retry tests Renamed tests, slightly tweaked testing parameters and added
DocStr and comments for better clarification.

Remove redundant sentry initialization With sentry-sdk, sentry client is now a global object that needs
to be initialized once per app. Thus WB should have only two: one
for tornado and the other for celery, with relevant integrations
respectively.

Disable logging as events for sentry With sentry-sdk, error level logs and above are sent to sentry as
event by default; info level logs and above are set as breadcrumbs
when issues happen.

This commit disables any level of logs being sent as event so that
WB Sentry is now free from noisy and pointless errors. In addition,
bumps the sentry-sdk from version 0.13.2 to 0.14.0.

support "bucket" key in cloudfiles settings  * When the OSF was updated to use googlecloud as the osfstorage
   backend, the default key for storing the bucket name changed from
   "container" to "bucket".  To work with both a modern OSF version
   and a pre-googlecloud OSF, support both in the cloudfiles provider.

 * An osfstorage file that was added in the cloudfile days will need
   to have its FileVersion records migrated in the OSF to use the
   "bucket" key or operations may fail with a KeyError
Remove context manager and fix tests for cloudfiles

Enable rackspace cloudfiles for aiohttp3  * Remove --ignore from pytest invocation since all providers are now
   converted.
Remove WB hack for GitLab ruby hash bug when getting file The bug: https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-foss/issues/31790

fix accidentally-passing tests  * Upgrading the pytest version revealed a couple of non-async tests
   that were being declared as async.  Fix these and correct the tests
   so they pass.

Fix download and tests for GitLab, update docstr The GL provider has been using a complicated hack for downloads due to
this issue: https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-ce/issues/31470,
which breaks the dedicated endpoint for direct raw file download.
Fortunately, the bug was fixed in GLv10.0 so that download has been
written to use the preferred and intuitive approach.

In addition, the hack would not work with aiohttp3 even if we kept it.
It needs to modify response headers directly within the object before
passing it to the response stream reader. aiohttp3 makes this
impossible: the `headers` attr is defined as a `@reify` property.  The
cache effect of `@reify` prevents modifying either `_headers` or
`headers`.
Add missing dependency requirements for flake8

Fix fixtures in GitLab tests  * Recent pytest versions complain when fixtures are invoked as
   functions.  Pass them as args instead.

fix DAZ for files-in-projects  * Update `path_from_metadata` to correctly handle files in projects.
   WB had been treating files as just a file entity under the project
   root, but they are actually stored in an implied article (which WB
   treats as a folder).

don't fail on checksum mismatch if hashing not done  * FigShare now returns a field in the response to upload requests
   that indicates whether hashing has completed.  If this is `false`,
   skip the checksum verification step.  Recent testing has shown that
   this completes quickly even for very large files.

Fix missing stream size when copy / move private files for figshare * Copy / Move private files / datasets from figshare to OSFStorage
  or any working provider including figshare fails. The problem is
  that the downloaded stream from the src-provider  has a None size
  during copy / move, which  breaks the upload-to-dest step which
  requires the size.

* The root problem: the download response for private files using
  the figshare API does not provide the Content-Length header that
  is used to build the response stream and to set the stream size.
  On the contrary, the download response for published files using
  figshare's backend S3 API provides the Content-Length header.

* The fix is to retrieve and save the file size in advance during
  the metadata request and then create the response stream using
  this size if the Content-Length header is not provided.

Fix celery task for figshare Move and copy fail for the figshare provider since `__new__()` in
the `FigshareProvider` class does not accept extra arguments such
as `is_celery_task` which was recently added for celery tasks. The
fix is simply adding the missing `**kwargs`.

Here is the related commit: https://github.com/CenterForOpenScience/waterbutler/commit/345b2d8d76a0e7425321624ea50b84831290e366

Completely fix the download for figshare - As for the figshare provider: When a file has been published,
  the figshare download request returns a redirection URL which
  downloads the file directly from its backend storage S3. The
  new request does not need any auth at all. More importantly,
  the default figshare auth header breaks the download since S3
  API does not understand figshare API. Thus, the provider must
  use `no_auth_header=True` to inform `super().make_request()`
  to drop the header.
- As for the core provider: Instead of modifying how headers are
  built with `build_headers()`, simply update `make_request()` to
  drop the `Authorization` header built into the headers.

Partially fix the download for figshare figshare directly calls `aiohttp.request()` with aiohttp 0.18 which
no longer works in aiohttp 3.5. Instead, rewrote the request making
process into using the updated `super().make_request()`.
Enable the figshare provider for aiohttp3

Remove context managers & fix tests  * Rewrite `async with ... as resp: ...` into `resp = await ...`

 * Fix googledrive tests to not instantiate fixtures directly

Use register_uri() for multi-URL registration in GitHub tests It doesn't make sense to use register_json_uri() for multi-URL
registration since the extra help this method provides does not
take any effects. Simply use `register_uri()` for this case.

Fix a response release issue for GitHub rate-limiting In aiohttp3, release() not only releases the response but also
closes the connection. This causes exception_from_response()
to encounter a connection already closed failure when trying to
release or consume the response. The fix: 1) Don't release the
response before calling _rl_handle_forbidden_error() and 2) let
_rl_handle_forbidden_error() and exception_from_response() take
care of it.

Fix missing headers when registering multiple URLs in GitHub tests aiohttp3 is more strict on response content-type, where .json()
would fail if the content-type were not provided or were incorrect.
However, the updated aiohttpretty still has the unpleasant bug that
.register_uri() ignores headers provided by .register_json_uri()
when multiple URL registrations are used. The fix is to explicitly
add the required header when calling .register_json_uri().

Fix mock response header value type in GitHub tests: int -> str aiohttpretty requires the `str` type on both header name and value,
which calls .encode() on both when building raw headers. Exceptions
would be thrown if int header values were provided.

Fix header, metadata and tests for S3 It is unknown why aiohttp 0.18.x stores HTTP response header names
in all-uppercase (e.g. CONTENT-LENGTH). aiohttp 3.5.x now uses the
more popular title case (e.g. Content-Length) which breaks the old
implementation (i.e. Key Error). The class `S3FileMetadataHeaders`
has been updated to fix this issue. Tests are fixed as well.
Enable the s3 provider for aiohttp3
bump aiohttp dep to latest version

Use kwarg ssl= instead of verify_ssl=  when init TCPConnector Kwarg verify_ssl= has been deprecated and no longer takes any
effect on setting the property _ssl of a TCPConnector instance.
Use ssl= instead. For details see the following links.

https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/3.5/aiohttp/connector.py#L733
https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/3.5/aiohttp/client_reqrep.py#L152
https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/v0.18.4/aiohttp/connector.py#L402

WB client session now supports customized connector For providers that use a customized connector such as owncloud,
the new session is created (if no session is found in the event
loop) with the given connector while an existing session simply
ignores (and closes) the new connector. Given that the session
is per loop for each instance, the existing session if found
must already have a connector with qualified customizations.

WB .make_request() now supports WebDAV methods aiohttp.ClientSession only has functions available for native HTTP
methods. For WebDAV (a protocol that extends HTTP) ones, WB lets
the ClientSession instance call _request() directly and then wraps
the return object with aiohttp.client._RequestContextManager.
Enable the owncloud provider for aiohttp3

misc. fixes for v3.6 upgrade  * Stop testing v3.5 on travis.

 * Update README to specify v3.6, remove v3.5-specific documentation.

 * Update links to external package versions in docs.

 * Mark WB as a v3.6 project in setup.py.

mark docstrings w/ escaped chars as raw  * Sphinx likes `**kwargs` to be escaped as `\*\*kwargs`, but python
   objects.  To avoid python's complaints, mark docstrings with those
   constructs as raw strings by prepending an `r` to the docstring
   delimiter.

 * While we're at it, fix the wrapping of a few method declarations.
Update docstrings and add TODOs for Dataverse
Enable code and test for the Dataverse provider

Fix request auth for Dataverse SWORD API using aiohttp3 aiohttp 3.5 (more specifically, starting aiohttp 0.22) requires
the req auth param to be of type BasicAuth when building the req
while aiohttp 0.18 politely shows a deprecation warning when a
tuple is used. The fix is to simply use a BasicAuth object init
with the tuple that was used as the req auth param before.

Only upload and delete are updated since they are the only two
actions that use the SWORD API.

switch from raven to sentry_sdk  * Sentry's `raven` library is deprecated and will be replaced by
   `sentry_sdk`.  `raven` interacts weirdly with the upgraded WB, so
   now is a good time to upgrade.

 * The sentry client is now a global object (analogous to a logger)
   instead of an object property.

 * Add sentry's Tornado integration to the tornado app and the Celery
   integration to the celery tasks.

stop preloading body in movecopy  * Tornado's `request.body` is not an awaitable coroutine anymore and
   does not need to be preloaded.

flake fixes and version bump  * Bump flake8 version to v3.5.0 and pyflakes to v1.6.0.  Bumping to
   flake8 v3.6.0 results in a slew of errors and warnings.  Hold off
   for now.

 * Fix flake error in googledrive that appears when upgrading to
   flake8 v3.5.0

 * Fix over-indented line error in preparation for possible flake
   upgrade

bump mypy python version  * This is a no-op now but will be needed to avoid "yield in async
   def" errors when we bump the mypy version.
add invoke tasks for newrelic startup/config
bump pytest modules to most recent versions

replace agent with native async generators  * Python v3.6 allows native async generators (`yield`s inside `async
   def`s) without requiring external modules.

future-proof test suite  * Prefer <foo>.assert_called_* methods over assert <foo>.called_*

 * test_create_mixin: replace a MockCoroutine that had been mocking a
   non-async method with a regular Mock object

 * Box: update base64 sha that had been incorrectly calculated.

 * Update celery task move/copy test infrastructure.  unittest-style
   test classes weren't working well with our task tests and fixtures.
   Switch to pytest style setup/teardown via conftest.py. Fixtures
   have been moved to conftest as well.

 * Add some clarifying documentation and debug logging to .tasks.core

update dropbox tests to work with updated unittest module  * Replace `assert mock.called_with()` with
   `mock.assert_called_with()`

 * `assert_called_with()` has gotten stricter about parameter order
   and missing args.  Fix order and add default parameters.

 * Checking all calls cannot be done with `assert_called_once_with`
   and different args.  Instead, build a list of calls using
   `unittest.mock.call` and pass this list to `assert_has_calls`

update aiohttpretty test decorators for pytest changes  * The newest version of pytest returns markers in `item.keywords` and
   no longer implements `item.get_marker`.

fix fixture that will break w/ pytest upgrade  * A future version of pytest will no longer allow fixtures to be
   invoked directly as methods.  These particular functions do not
   need to be fixtures, as they will be created anew each time they
   are invoked.

fix asyncio method that will fail in py3.7  * `async` is a reserved keyword in py3.7 and is no longer allowed to
   be a method name.  In v3.7 `create_task` is the preferred
   replacement for `asyncio.async`, but it doesn't exist in earlier
   pythons.  `ensure_future` is an alias that exists in 3.5, 3.6, and
   3.7.

remove old pin on certifi  * The python module `certifi` was pinned to a very old version to
   work around issues with Rackspace.  It has been 4+ years since those
   issues were encountered, and perhaps it's time to retire them.

pin development dependencies  * Using `pip freeze`, pin the currently installed version of unpinned
   development dependencies.  This includes:
   - ipdb
   - ipython
   - pyflakes
   - python-coveralls
   - redis

 * Update aiohttpretty to pull from COS's `develop` branch.

move invalid json test from fuzzing to movecopy  * In v1, only move/copy expects the body of the request to be json.
   Move the invalid json test from test_fuzzing to test_movecopy.
remove unused import from v1 test fixtures

grab gosu from apt-get in Dockerfile  * gosu v1.10 started being shipped with debian as of the `stretch`
   release.  Install from apt-get instead of `curl`-ing it from the
   github release page.

upgrade tornado to v6 + add newrelic  * Upgrade Tornado dep to v6 to support newrelic instrumenting.
   Newrelic has added async support, but requires Tornado v6+.

honor defined query parameter precedence  * Some legacy code in the `metadata` and `download` endpoints was
   granting `revision` and `version` query parameters precedence over
   that defined in `_interpret_query_parameters`.  Remove that code,
   so that revision behavior is consistent within the provider.

remove vestigial kwarg from FigshareProjectProvider  * While adding `**kwargs` to the provider constructors, an unused
   `child=False` kwarg was found in FigshareProjectProvider. From
   looking at the git history, it appears to be an artifact of
   development and has never been used.
Update docstring for dropbox download on header "Dropbox-API-Result"

add flag to BaseProvider to mark if it's running in celery  * Add `is_celery_task` property to BaseProvider.  This allows the
   providers to implement behavior only appropriate for long-running
   and potentially asynchronous operations like moves/copies.  The
   GitHub provider uses this to decide when to engage its
   rate-limiting logic.  Previously, the move/copy celery tasks had
   been adding a `task_id` property to the provider post-construction.

 * To support this, the constructors for all of the providers have
   been updated to accept `**kwargs` and to pass them on to the base
   class's constructor.  `waterbutler.utils.make_provider` has also
   been updated to pass along the kwargs when constructing an object.

 * Update GH tests to accomodate this change.

rename exception-handling method  * Rename it to indicate that it handles exceptions.

 * Have it return the exception instead of raising it itself.

 * Don't release the response inside the method.  The calling function
   should be responsible for that.
expand tests for rate-limit error handling
support case where reset time ticks over mid-wait

simplify rate-limit calculations; update tests to match  * Squash logic from `_rl_update_req_rate` into `_rl_add_more_tokens`.

 * Reserved tokens are based off last reported rate limit, which means
   it only changes after a successful request.  Move the calculation
   to after the response is received instead of recalculating it
   multiple times per wait.

 * Make `rl_req_rate` a local variable instead of an instance
   variable.  It's only used within `_rl_add_more_tokens` and does not
   require a historical value.

remove check for reset time expired  * Remove an optimization to make the algorithm easier to understand.
   This optimization would allow a request that was accumulating
   tokens to complete faster if the rate-limit reset in the middle of
   token generation.  This had no effect when the refresh rate was at
   its minimum.  It could only affect the (relatively) fast
   pre-reserve-threshold request limit requests, and it would affect
   only the first one.  Since the maximum theoretical wait time for a
   minimally-slow refresh rate is 100s, this optimization seems
   unnecessary.

Relocate and add docstrs/TODOs for `._rl_*` methods  - Move all of these methods to the bottom of the `provider.py` file
   for consistency of how we order methods across all providers

Enable filesystem for aiohttp3 The FileSystem provider is for local develop only, which replaces
the GCloud as the storage provider for OSF Storage. No request is
made and all are disk access, which works as it is with aiohttp3.

Enable bitbucket for aiohttp3 The bitbucket provider is read-only and only uses `.make_request()`,
which works as it is with aiohttp3 as expected.

Add a note and TODO for using dropbox_request() properly Unlike other providers, this is not a general wrapper than can
either be applied to all or be thrown away, which makes it out
of the scope of the oathpit project (i.e. aiohttp3 upgrade).
Refactor the dropbox provider for aiohttp3

gh: recalculate request rate on every iteration  * Previously, the GH provider had tried to optimize itself by only
   recalculating the refresh rate every 10 seconds.  This is
   (currently) an unnecessary complication that just makes the code
   harder to follow.  Update the provider to re-calculate the rate
   on every check.

gh: add tokens on each add_token step  * Update `_rl_add_more_tokens()` to add tokens on every call.
   Previously, it had waited until it could add at least one full
   token before actually increasing the token count.  This meant
   keeping track of an additional state variable, the time since we
   last added a token.  Instead, allow `_rl_add_more_tokens` to add
   fractional tokens less than one.  This allows the provider get rid
   of one intermediate instance variable (`._rl_tokens_updated`) and
   will allow debugging to show incremental progress towards reaching
   the token threshold.

 * Update type signature of `_rl_add_more_tokens` to reflect that it
   does *not* return a bool.  It now returns nothing.

 * Update comments and docstrings

don't log every request made in metrics payload  * For large move/copy actions, this can result in a huge metrics
   payload.  Instead of logging the actual request urls and responses,
   keep a tally of how many requests succeed and how many fail.
remove unused vars from github tests

gh: clean up error handling for params with multiple vals  * If WB receives a request with multiple instances of the same query
   params, it will ignore that param as long as there is another
   correctly-formatted param it can use.  If not, WB will throw a 400
   Bad Request error with an explanatory error message.

gh: refactor _interpret_query_params to be clearer  * Create three distinct parameter lists to make it easier to
   understand the purpose of each.  No functional changes.

gh: validate commit shas with length testing.  * GitHub does not accept abbreviated commit SHAs, so add length
   testing as a heuristic for determining if a given ref is a SHA or
   branch name.

 * git will be transitioning to using SHA-256 in a future release.
   sha256-names are 64 hexdigits long, while sha1-names are 40
   hexdigits. git will support both types of names. Update the
   _looks_like_sha method to check a list of valid sha
   lengths. 40 is still the only default value, but the setting can be
   easily updated to add 64 when git+sha256 is released.

gh: fix revisions method support for branch/sha query params  * Update the `revisions` method to use a commit sha or branch ref (if
   available) as the start point for file history.  It had erroneously
   been using the uncommon file_sha query parameter.  Since this was
   usually `None`, the provider would fall back to using the default
   branch as the start point.

 * Remove `sha` arg from `revisions()` signature.  v1 doesn't pass
   this, and it should always be `None`.

gh: allow "branch" query param to be a commit sha  * Add `branch` to the end of the list of possible query parameters
   containing a commit SHA.  Since the previous commit, it was
   discovered that some parts of the OSF were passing the `branch`
   query param with a commit SHA.  `branch` is now the lowest-priority
   sha-like query param, while also being the highest-priority
   branch-like param.

add tests for chunked upload nonroot files  * Improve the chunked upload tests for root-{upload,update}s. The
   previous tests were not very informative, testing only that the
   registered call was hit and that the data structure we told it to
   return was returned.

   * The returned data structure test is tautological and has been
     removed.  Remove unused fixtures from chunked upload test
     methods.  The response has been replaced with dummy data to
     emphasize this.

   * The has_call test has been updated to test that the data SENT to
     Box is correctly formed based off the rootedness and
     pre-existence of the target file.

 * Add tests for nonroot-{upload,update} following the example of
   root-*.

 * Sort keys when encoding the JSON payload for the chunked upload
   session endpoint.  Our test library will only check for naive
   equality when comparing data payloads, so it is important we define
   a canonical ordering for keys.

Use either file ID or parent folder ID for box chunked upload  * During box chunked upload session creation, WB should EITHER
   include the file ID in the session creation URL (if the file
   already exists) OR provide the parent folder ID in the data payload
   (if the file is new).

 * Update Box chunked upload to provide the correct parent folder ID
   for new file uploads.  The code was always uploading to the project
   root instead of the parent folder's id.  This is fine if the parent
   folder IS the project root, but it meant that files larger than the
   chunked upload threshold (default: 50Mb) couldn't be uploaded to a
   subfolder.

   * If a large file was uploaded to the project root, it could still
     be successfully moved to a subdirectory, as that is a separate
     action from uploads/updates.  But if a file with an identical
     name was already present in the root, the Box provider would hang
     with an unhandled error caused by the filename conflict.  This
     error means that it is unlikely that any data was accidentally
     overwritten because of this bug.
Fixed path validation v0 & project upload tests

Fixed the rest of figshare provider tests by updating old fixtures - Tests fixed: TestProjectCRUD, TestArticleMetadata, Test ArticleCRUD
- Changes made to crud/errors/root_provider json:
  - Added missing "url_public_html" and "url_private_html"
  - Changed "defined_type": 3 to defined_type": 1 so that old file
    fixtures remain to be file during unit test.
  - Changed "defined_type": 4 to defined_type: 3 (after the above
    change) so that the tests cover new folder type 3.
  - ("is_public" or "published_date" already exist, no need to add)

Rewrote test_provider.TestProjectMetadata for figshare * A full refactor with new project/article/file fixtures
* Renamed test names and added DocStr to breifly describe each test
* Minor improvements on code and style

Fixed figshare metadata test Since the figshare web view link fix is partial, new metadata
fixtures for both private and public articles (file and folder)
are added and used for refactored metadata tests.

Fixed the public flag for path during path validation for figshare - Previous way of identifying public paths no longer works since the
  "url" property for both private and public articles now shares the
  same format. Use the "published_date" property instead.
- In addition, fixed the loop check by 1) breaking when found 2) err
  if no match after loop ends

Ignore the public flag and only build private API URL for fighsare - public API URL does not work as currently implemented in WB
- public API URL is designed only for the WIP collection stuff

Refactored Fileset to Dataset for figshare provider There are only 2 occurrences where "Fileset" is explicitly used:
provider init and folder creation. For the former, added Dataset
and keep Fileset; for the latter, replaced Fileset with Dataset.

use fixed chunk size when reading from stream iterators  * aiohttp now calls `.read()` without a chunk size argument when

   base classes (BaseStream, MultiStream, CutoffStream,
   Base64EncodeStream) implement to work with aiohttp v3.  h/t

   that will take more time to develop.

Rewrite how core WB makes async request and handles response - A new method .make_request_with_session() replaces the glorious
  .make_request(). Due to the fact that aiohttp3's context manager
  does not work well for WB, the new one requires a client session to
  be provided and carefully managed by the calling provider. WB's core
  simply uses this session to make requests and pass back responses.
  Everything else stays the same mostly.

  the legacy .make_request() is kept alive and now calls the new one

add back filename parameter to content-disposition header  * Add the `filename` parameter to the Content-Disposition header

Add CutoffStream class to read subset of existing stream  * Most providers have limits on how big a file can be uploaded in a
   single request.  Some providers support uploading larger files by
   "chunking" uploads: breaking a file into multiple pieces, uploading
   them individually, then reassembling them on the providers side.
   Each provider sets its own limit on the max size of a single chunk,
   but usually they are multi-megabyte chunks.

   WB receives a single stream during an upload.  To chunk this
   without downloading and manually partitioning the file requires a
   stream reader class that can read up to `n` bytes, then stop
   without closing the original stream.  The WB stream classes inherit
   from `asyncio.StreamReader`, whose `readexactly(n)` and `read(n)`
   methods appear to support this use case.  They do, sort of.  They
   attempt to read all `n` bytes into a chunk in memory before sending
   it off the the provider.  This means that 1) uploading a 10 Mb
   chunk requires 10 Mb of memory, and 2) all 10 Mb must be fetched
   from the uploader before being sent.  1 could quickly lead to
   memory exhaustion in WB if multiple uploads happen at the same
   time.  2 can cause uploads to fail. If the uploader is slow to send
   data to WB and fill the chunk, the receiving provider may close the
   connection as inactive.

   The solution is to continuously send smaller subchunks of data to
   the provider, terminating after the overall chunk size is reached.
   This is actually how the `asyncio.StreamReader.read()` method is
   intended to function, but confusion between what `read()` calls a
   chunk size and what the provider calls a chunk size led to failures
   in cross-provider move/copies into Figshare, the only provider at
   the time of this commit that supports chunked uploads.

   The new CutoffStream class takes an existing stream object and the
   provider-given chunk size (superchunk) and continuously reads and
   feeds subchunks.  After each subchunk read, a bytes-thus-far
   counter is updated.  The CutoffStream stops reading when
   bytes-thus-far equals the superchunk size.  Only subchunk bytes of
   data are stored in memory at a time.

move url evocation inside the retry loop  * In 0.38.2, the googlecloud provider was updated to provide a
   function as the url parameter to `BaseProvider.make_request`.
   Since googlecloud urls are signed and can expire, it must delay
   generation until right before issuing.  Otherwise, if the first
   request fails, the second may not get issued until after the
   signature has expired.

   Unfortunately, `.make_request` was evoking the url function outside
   of the retry loop.  This resulted in the same signed url being used
   for each retry.  Moving this inside the retry loop will cause new
   urls to be generated for each retry request.

add post-task cleanup for osfstorage tasks  * The osfstorage provider kicks off two tasks after upload; one to
   backup the file to Amazon Glacier and one to generate parity files
   that are sent to a bucket on the storage backend provider.  Since
   both tasks run in parallel and need a copy of the uploaded file to
   work, neither could be responsible for deleting it when done.
   Instead this work would need to be done periodically by an admin to
   keep the disk from filling up.

   Both tasks are now included in a Celery chord.  When all the tasks
   in a chord are done, it runs another task.  In this case, the chord
   will run a cleanup task after both other tasks finish.  To make
   this simpler, each upload is moved to a temporary directory where
   it and its generated parity files lived.  This temporary directory
   is removed by the cleanup task.

   The parity and archive tasks tests have been commented out rather
   than updated, since a simpler approach may be implemented soon.

Send along user ID when asking for children metadata from the osf  [#SVCS-689]

 * osfstorage is being updated to include a flag in file metadata that
   will indicate if the requesting user has seen the most recent
   version of the file.  To help the OSF properly determine this,
   update WB to send along the requesting user's id when asking for
   the metadata of all files in a given directory.

   The requesting user is not the same as the authorizing user.  If
   Barbara asks for the contents of an osfstorage directory created by
   Alice, Barbara is the *requesting* user, while Alice is the
   *authorizing* user.  WB first verifies that Barbara has the
   necessary access to the file, but uses a shared secret to retrieve
   metadata about the file.  This change is necessary to inform the
   OSF who is behind the request.

 * The osfstorage folder children response is updated to include a new
   flag, `latestVersionSeen`.  If this flag is `null`, the requesting
   user has never seen *any* version of the file.  If it is `true`,
   the user has seen the latest version of the file.  If it is
   `false`, the user has seen a previous version of the file, but not
   the most recent one.  This flag will be exposed through the
   `extra.latestVersionSeen` flag in OsfStorageFileMetadata.

 * Due to a quirk in WB and the OSF, the latestVersionSeen flag will
   only be correctly set on the responses from folder metadata list
   requests.  Neither service correctly handles requests for
   previous-version metadata for individual files.

 * Update tests to include latestVersionSeen in children response.

Merge branch 'feature/range-header-handling' into develop  * Teach WB to correctly interpret incoming Range headers. It had been
   returning one more byte than requested due to a misunderstanding of
   how a utility library worked.  The issue manifested as the
   inability of Safari to play videos from WB.  @abought and
   @Johnetordoff discovered that Safari makes a two-byte range request
   before playing the file.  WB was returning a three-byte response,
   causing Safari to refuse to play the videos.

 * Teach WB to release partial responses.  A side effect of fixing the
   range handling was that partial responses were never reaching their
   EOF.  Streams only signal EOF when a read is issued after the feed
   has been exhausted.  Since partial response return exactly the
   number of bytes within them, this never occurs.

 * Add Range header support to Figshare, GitLab, and the filesystem
   providers.  Bitbucket, GitLab, and Dataverse do not support this
   header and will continue to return full responses if received.

 * Add range header support tests for all providers that support them.

 * Add logger modules to all providers.

 * These changes are only being made for v1.  v0 is deprecated and is
   expected to be removed soon.

   do this, the `aiohttp.request()` call was replaced with a call to

add range header to GitHub download method  * GitHub doesn't support the Range header.  Draw attention to this

manually implement Range header support for GitLab  * Strip down file responses from GitLab to the requested range size
   and construct an response object with a status of 206 Partial and
   the Content-Range header added.

   GitLab does not respect the Range header and always returns the
   entire file blob Base64-encoded.  Since we have to decode the
   response into memory anyway, we can manually trim the bytes stream
   down to the requested range.

 * Add tests for range header handling.

add logger to bitbucket, log download properties

add range header to Bitbucket download method  * Bitbucket doesn't support the Range header, but perhaps one day it
   will.  Draw attention to this fact by including it in the
   download() signature and documenting it in the Quirks.  Start
   passing the Range header to the Bitbucket v1 download endpoint.
   BB's v2 API was tested locally and also does not support the Range
   header.

close partial responses after writing  * Manually close partial downloads after writing content.  Regular
   downloads (not Range-limited) via ResponseStreamReader close
   themselves automatically, calling `self.response.release()` when
   the stream EOF is reached.  Partial downloads were not doing that,
   because they read the exact amount of data in the stream and stop
   just short of EOF.  When the request finished, aiohttp would
   complain about an unreleased request.

   To remedy this, after writing out the data from the stream, the v1
   file_download action checks if the stream is a partial stream and a
   ResponseStreamReader and manually releases the embedded response if
   so.

add function for handling tornado's weird range parsing  * Add a new method, waterbutler.server.utils.parse_request_range, to
   parse Range header values into a tuple of byte positions
   representing the range requested, inclusively.  `bytes=0-1` will be
   parsed into `(0, 1)`.  It does not currently handle ranges of the
   form `bytes=-5` or ranges where the end position is less than the
   start position (`bytes=9-2`) and will throw an exception if either
   is encountered.

   WB had been using Tornado's `httputil._parse_request_range` to
   parse Range header values.  This function will return a tuple of
   list-slicing-compatible indicies, where the second value is
   exclusive. For `bytes=0-1` it would return the tuple `(0, 2)`.  WB
   had been assuming the indicies are the inclusive byte positions and
   was returning one more byte than expected.

 * Added a new exception, InvalidHeaderError, to indicate an
   unsupported Range format.  This exception was added to the
   pickling/unpickling tests.

add logging to v1 metadata mixin  * log range header, stream size, and bytes received to help diagnose

add flag to log payload if download req comes from MFR  * If WB receives a download request that includes an MFR-identifying

Handle all github revision-identification parameters  <This commit is a re-application of 9b541f2be708, which was reverted
 in 5fdc63f2d41e.  The commit message has been updated to better
 reflect the intention and implementation.>

 Over the life of WB, the github provider has accepted the following
 parameters to identify the ref (commit or branch) that the path
 entity is to be found on: "ref", "branch", "version", "sha",
 "revision".  Worse, sometimes the values are commit SHAs and other
 times are branch names.  Worserer (sic), some queries contain two or
 three of these parameters at the same time.

 WB strives to maintain backcompat, so the following method tries to
 divine the user intention as much as possible, using the following
 heuristics:

 * If both a commit SHA and branch name are provided, the commit SHA
   should be used, since it is more specific.

 * Each parameter will be checked.  If present and not equal to the
   empty string, it will be run through the _looks_like_sha method
   to decide whether it is a SHA or branch name.

 * The order in which the query parameters are tested differs for
   commit SHAs and branches. The order for commit SHAs from highest
   precedence to lowest precedence is: "ref", "version", "sha",
   "revision".  "ref" is returned in the action links for file and
   folder metadata, and so takes precendence.  "version" is the most
   common parameter, used heavily in the OSF.  "sha" occurs
   occasionally, but despite the name can be either a commit SHA or
   branch name. "revision" does not appear to be in regular use
   anymore, but has cropped up in development in old metadata entries.

 * The order for branch names from highest priority to lowest priority
   is: "branch", "ref", "version", "sha", "revision". "branch" is used
   by fangorn and so far appears to always be a branch name.  The
   others follow the same priority for commit SHAs.

 * If none of the query parameters are present or contain a valid
   commit SHA/branch name, WB will fall back to the default branch
   for the repo.

ensure all exceptions can survive unpickling  * Usually python objects are unpickled by creating an uninitialized
   instance with __new__ then updating its __dict__ with the saved
   parameters.  Objects that inherit from Exception behave a little
   differently; before the __dict__ is updated, the child class's
   __init__ is called with whatever positional args were passed in
   the call to Exception.__init__().  Since WaterButlerError calls
   Exception.__init__() with a single integer argument, every
   exception that inherits from it must survive instantiation with the
   same signature.

   This means that no child of WaterButlerError can have a signature
   with anything other than one positional argument.  It must not call
   any non-integer methods on the positional arg.  kwargs are not
   passed as part of the faux __init__ call, so a class must be able
   to be instantiated with defaults only.  It is not necessary that
   the exception be meaningful when called this way.  Its __dict__ is
   updated immediately afterward, so its state will be made consistent
   with its pre-pickling self.

   A new test file, test_exceptions.py, was added to enforce this.  It
   tries creating every available exception with a single integer arg.
   A new exception that cannot pass this will be considered buggy.

   Some of the existing exceptions had to be redesigned to accomodate
   this new restriction.  Their usages in the codebase have been
   updated, too.

   * UnsupportHTTPMethodError: formerly took two positional arguments,
     has been updated to take one positional and one kwarg. The kwarg
     for the list of supported methods was modified to support being
     passed a None.

   * FolderNamingConflict: relied on a `name` kwarg or its positional
     argument, `path`, being a string.  Updated to take a single
     `name` positional argument, which is passed to a format
     string. Resulting error message was simplified, and tests were
     updated to match.

   * NamingConflict: relied on a `name` kwarg or its positional
     argument, `path`, being a WaterButlerPath.  Updated to take a
     single `name` positional argument, which is passed to a format
     string. Resulting error message was simplified, and tests were
     updated to match.  Callers were updated to pass `path.name` as
     the arg in place of the full object.

   * GitHubUnsupportedRepoError: formerly took no positional
     arguments, updated to take a single, unused dummy argument.

 * Reformatted Dropbox-specific exceptions, updated tests, and added
   unpickling tests.

reorganize exception hierarchy  * One source of confusion in trying to understand WB's exception
   hierarchy us that there were two inconsitently defined classes of
   errors.  One type of error is the developer-defined exception,
   built to reflect an expected and accounted-for error condition.
   The other is the unhandled-provider exception.  Since we don't have
   full control over external providers, we sometimes get unexpected
   responses from them.  When that happens, we need to throw an
   exception that contains the received status code and error message.

   Unhandled-provider exceptions are thrown from the
   waterbutler.core.provider.make_request method, which calls
   waterbutler.core.exceptions.exception_from_response to build the
   error.  These providers must all have the same signature, since
   they are being programattically built.

   Developer-defined errors may accept more specialized arguments,
   define specific message strings, and have default error
   codes. Their signatures do not have to follow a spec (this is
   ominous foreshadowing, see the next commit).

   The hierarchies of both types of errors were entangled, leading to
   confusion errors, and misuse.  The unhandled-provider errors now
   have their own parent class, UnhandledProviderError, which is not
   shared with developer-defined exceptions.  Developer-defined
   exceptions continue to inherit from ProviderError.

   Related changes:

   * exception_from_response's default error class is now
     UnhandledProviderError, rather than ProviderError.

   * make_request also now defaults to UnhandledProviderError

   * make_request calls in the figshare and googledrive providers were
     updated to throw unhandled-provider errors, instead of
     developer-defined errors.

   * docstrings were added and the exception definitions shuffled
     about to group similar exceptions together.

 * UnsupportedHTTPMethodError's parent changed from PluginError to
   WaterButlerError, since it is conceivably useful by the core server
   classes, not just the auth handlers.

get HTTP status enums from HTTPStatus  * The local REPL didn't like the pattern of importing http then

check hashes on upload, where possible; add hashes to metadata  * Some providers include content hashes as part of their upload
   response.  Update WB to calculate a corresponding hash and compare.
   If they are different, corruption must have happened.  Throw an
   error so the user is notified.

   In addition, some providers return hash data in standard metadata
   responses.  WB should be returning this in our standard file
   metadata responses.

 * Per provider explanations:

   * box: Returns a sha1 of the file on upload and in metadata.  Hash
     available in file metadata in the `extra.hashes.sha1` key.

   * cloudfiles: Returns an md5 as the etag on file upload and in
     metadata.  Hash available in file metadata in the
     `extra.hashes.md5` key.

   * dataverse: Returns an md5 in file metadata, which WB must request
     after upload.  Hash available in file metadata in the
     `extra.hashes.md5` key.

   * dropbox: Returns a dropbox-specific hash[1], so WB does not
     assert on upload.  Hash is available in the
     `extra.hashes.dropbox` key.

   * figshare: Returns an md5 in file metadata, which WB must request
     after upload.  Hash available in file metadata in the
     `extra.hashes.md5` key.

   * github: Returns a git blob hash, which is the sha1 of the blob
     content with the string 'blob $blob_size\0' prefixed to it.  Hash
     available in file metadata in the `extra.hashes.git` key.

   * googledrive: Returns an md5 on upload and in metadata.  Hash
     available in file metadata in the `extra.hashes.md5` key.

   * owncloud: Does not provide any file hashes.

   * s3: Returns an md5 as the etag on file upload and in metadata.
     Hash available in file metadata in the `extra.hashes.md5` key.

  [1] https://www.dropbox.com/developers/reference/content-hash

accomadate bug in gitlab file metadata serialization  * When accessing the file data endpoint in the GitLab API, if the
   filename ends with `.txt` GitLab's response will be serialized as a
   Ruby hash rather than JSON.  This is avoidable by percent-encoding
   the period in the extension, but RFC 3986 recommends NOT encoding
   periods. In addition, if we manually construct the url with an
   encoded period, aiohttp decodes it again before sending.

   Rather than trying to mess with aiohttp internals (which would
   affect all providers), we will instead try to convert the Ruby
   serialization to json, then deconvert.  The metadata returned by
   this endpoint is limited to just a few fields, most of which have
   well-defined representations.  The current naive approach is
   adopted from a StackOverflow question.  We may need to make this
   more robust, since the `file_name` and `file_path` fields may

Restore per-incoming-request throttling  * Our throttling implementation intended to keep track of how many
   simultaneous requests it received, but the incremented counter was
   not being saved, so it always appeared to be one request.  This
   meant that an operation that caused many parallel requests at
   once (e.g. batch-uploading via the OSF's file browser) would bypass
   our throttling, possibly causing us to hit rate and resource
   limits.  Thankfully, the greediest request types (recursive moves,
   copies, and download-as-zip) have their own built-in limiting.

   base folder always ending with a slash.  To fix this, if the

fix tests broken by the fix for bpo-28703, present in py >= v3.5.3  * The fix for bpo-28703 (https://bugs.python.org/issue28703) taught
   the iscoroutinefunction() to be stricter in its testing.  Prior to
   this, it would return True for mock objects.  With this fix
   (applied in 3.5.3 and 3.6.0), it now returns False.

   This was causing test failures in some of the v0 test suites,
   because we were relying on the ability to detect when we should
   unrwap our MockCoroutines.  With 3.5.3 and above, the MockCoroutine
   was not being unwrapped, causing the await call to return a
   coroutine instead of the function results.

   To work around this MockCoroutine has been taught to to slip past
   iscoroutinefunction() by importing the variable that it uses to
   identify a coroutine function.  This is only applied on Python >=
   v3.5.3, as this variable was not present before then.

   3.5.3, where an unneccesary event loop was being started to get the
   results of an upload coroutine.  This is a v0-only test issue.
"Every major open-source project has its own style guide:  a set of conventions (sometimes arbitrary) about how to write  code for that project." [#SVCS-351]

update googledrive provider file revision handling  * Some OSF users were reporting that they had files which they could
   view on GoogleDrive but not MFR.  The core problem was that they
   had read-only permission for these files, and the Google Drive API
   returns a 403 when requesting the revision list for such files. WB
   was failing to handle this gracefully and was returning a 500.

   While investigating this, it was discovered that there are some
   other quirks in the provider.  Readonly Google Docs were primarily
   affected, since they require an extra call to the revisions API.

   There was also some inconsistency in how we handled revisions.
   This appears to have been a known problem for some time.  To avoid
   it an early attempt was made to signal these troublesome files by
   appending a sentinel value to the revision id.  However, WB was
   handling the sentinel value inconsistently, meaning it was
   sometimes respected and sometimes not.

   This commits attempts to clean this up and provide consistent
   behavior for all combinations of file type, editability, and
   revision format. The behaviors are:

    * If a download or metadata request is made without a revision
      parameter for a file of any type or editability, WB will
      download or provide metadata for the latest version.

    * If a download or metadata request is made and the revision ends
      with the sentinel value, WB will download or provide metadata
      for the latest version.  This is true for all files.

    * If a file is read-only (user has view or commenting permissions)
      and a revision is given that DOES NOT end with the sentinel
      value, WB will respond with a 404 Not Found. Read-only files do
      not have revisions.

    * If a file is editable and a revision is given that DOES NOT end
      with the sentinel value, WB will respond with a 404 if the
      requested revision does not exist on Google Drive.  Otherwise,
      it will return the content or metadata for the file at that
      revision.

safely encode most BB file names  * Bitbucket allows all characters except / in filenames. Bitbucket
   API urls have the following requirements for character encoding:

   * must encode: \#%?
   * optional encode: [{]}|"<>~`!@ $^&*()+=,;:'
   * encoding not used: ._-

   Support for the percent sign in file names is spotty right now, b/c
   the version of furl we use to build urls is buggy wrt %:

   ````
   In [12]: furl.furl('http://foo.com/m%o/').url
   Out[12]: 'http://foo.com/m%o/'

   In [13]: furl.furl('http://foo.com/m%25o/').url
   Out[13]: 'http://foo.com/m%o/'

   In [14]: furl.furl('http://foo.com/m%2525o/').url
   Out[14]: 'http://foo.com/m%o/'

   In [32]: furl.furl('http://foo.com/a%23%3F%5Ce/?bar=baz').url
   Out[32]: 'http://foo.com/a%23%3F%5Ce/?bar=baz'

   In [33]: furl.furl('http://foo.com/a%23%3F%5Ce%25/?bar=baz').url
   Out[33]: 'http://foo.com/a#?\\e%/?bar=baz'
   ````

core zip stream generator: add max arg of 1 to ''.replace()  * No count limit was being passed in the calls to replace() in
   core.util.ZipStreamGenerator.  The replace was intended to strip

   end up with a top-level file called `subbar.txt`, because

Prevent github provider from creating empty commits.  When an operation is performed on a github repository that leaves it
 in the same state as before, WB should not create an empty commit
 that contains no functional changes.  Examples where this can happen:

   * A user updates a file with the same content as it had before

   * A user copies a file from a directory in the repo over an
     existing file that has the same contents.

 In both cases, the tree is unmodified, and no new commit is
 needed. In the case of the update, we must issue an extra request to
 test if the new blob sha is the same as the old blob sha for the
 updated file.  In the case of the copy, we have the root tree sha
 from before the operation.  When we upload the new tree contents to
 GH, it returns the sha of the new root tree.  We can compare them,
 and if they are the same avoid creating a new commit.

Don't allow google docs to be accessed without an extension  * WaterButler used to address Google Docs (.gdoc, .gsheet, .gslides,
   .gdraw) without extensions.  This lead to confusion when two GDocs
   of different types had the same name, e.g. `thesis.gdoc` and
   `thesis.gsheet` would both be identified as `thesis`.  WB started
   appending extensions to GDocs in returned metadata with v0.29.0.
   An oversight allowed them to still be accessed without the
   extension.  This has been fixed, and a Google Doc called `foo` must
   now be accessed as `foo.gdoc`.

centralize callback logging WB logs mutating actions to a callback given by the auth provider.
This logging was happening in five different places in the code:

 * .server.api.v0.core.BaseProviderHandler._send_hook
 * .server.api.v0.core.BaseCrossProviderHandler._send_hook
 * .server.api.v1.provider.__init__.ProviderHandler._send_hook
 * .task.copy.copy
 * .task.move.move

This commit moves all logging code to one subroutine,
.core.utils.log_to_callback.  This subroutine takes a source LogPayload
and an optional destination LogPayload and constructs a common log
payload to be sent to the logging server.

The LogPayload class is a simple wrapper class to hold the logged
object's parent resource, serving provider, and a path or metadata
object to be serialized.  It serves to enforce the argument contract and
to format the log object in a common way.

endpoint also returns the file contents along with the metadata.

is bigger than 1Mb.  `validate_v1_path` has been updated to request a
recursive tree listing, which it can then search through for the given
path.

stricter "PUT to create" semantics   Despite an earlier commit that was supposed to enforce stricter
  semantics on PUT create requests, our provider were behaving in many
  different ways on duplicate requests.  Here are our expected
  semantics:

  1. `PUT /$provider/?kind=folder&name=i-am-a-folder`

    If a folder named `i-am-a-folder` doesn't already exist, create it and
    return 201 Created.  If it does exists, return 409 Conflict.

  2. `PUT /$provider/?kind=file&name=i-am-a-file`

    If a file named `i-am-a-file` doesn't already exist, create it and
    return 201 Created.  If it does exists, return 409 Conflict.

  3. `PUT /$provider/i-am-a-file?kind=file`

    If a file named `i-am-a-file` doesn't already exist, throw a 404 Not
    Found. If it does exists, update the file and return 200 OK.

  osfstorage and box were violating example 2, because the `name`
  parameter wasn't being translated into the ID needed to check for
  existence.  googledrive was failing because its metadata fails if
  called on a WaterButlerPath whose ID hasn't been established yet.

  **THIS MAY BREAK EXISTING CODE** Because I'm dumb, I forgot to update
  the API documentation here and in the OSF.  Example 1 was documented
  correctly, but occasionally allowed overwriting or additional creates
  in non-osfstorage providers.  After this commit, it no longer should.
  Example 2 was incorrectly documented, so anyone relying on `PUT
  /?kind=file&name=foo` to update a file should switch to using Example
  3.  If you were use on the `/links/upload` attribute of the
  JSON-API response, you won't need to do anything, as that gave the
  correct url.  Example 3 is unchanged.

handle exists == [] in renaming logic Annoyingly, the `exists()` method returns the result of `metadata()` if

Enable deletes against root folder with confirm_delete=1 WB had been silently allowing DELETE requests to be issued against the
stoarge provider roots (e.g. DELETE /resources/mst3k/provider/box/),
but handled them inconsistently.  Some providers would clear out the
root folder, some would 500, some would delete the actual storage root
folder on the provider, breaking the OSF addon.

This commit makes DELETEs against the storage root officially
supported.  When a DELETE is issued against the root, WB will delete
all files and folders underneath the root, but will not delete the
root folder itself.  Since this behavior is dangerous and differs
semantically from deletes againt other folders, we have decided to
require that the caller pass the query argument `confirm_delete=1`
with the call.  Otherwise, WB will respond with a 400 Bad Request.
`confirm_delete` is only required for deletes against the storage
root.

update s3 provider to work w/ sigv4 regions The Frankfort and Seoul AWS regions require that requests be signed with
their v4 protocol.  The code to handle this is in boto, but the
generate_url_sigv4 function doesn't include query parameters in the
signing protocol.  That means that when we issue a request with query
parameters, the signature we report fails to match with that calculated
by Amazon.

I've updated the boto code to handle this and updated the s3 provider to
always pass all query parameters and headers to the generate_url
functions.  sigv2 allowed some to be omitted, but v4 is much stricter.

fix cross-resource dropbox move metadata error  * For intra_move and intra_copy, dropbox metadata figures out the relative path
   of the file by stripping the parent folder from the full path.  When
   moving a file from one node's dropbox to another's, we were

Fixes: [#OSF-5516]

s3: support periods in bucketnames for all regions A bogus error message in the OSF S3 addon revealed some shenanigans
in how we handle bucket names outside the US (N. Virginia) region.
Amazon permits bucket names that follow subdomain-naming conventions
(labels separated by periods).  WB had been accessing buckets using
the subdomain calling format, which would access a bucket named 'foo'
at `https://foo.s3.amazonaws.com/`.  However, wildcard nested
subdomain certificates are deprecated, and Pythons newer than 2.7.9
will throw a certificate checking error if you try to access them.
IOW a bucket named 'foo' will still work, but a bucket named 'foo.bar'
will try to connect to `https://**foo.bar**.s3.amazonaws.com/` and
will fail validation.

`boto`, the library WB uses to communicate with S3, supports another
calling format that avoids this issue, the `OrdinaryCallingFormat`.
Under OCF, a call to a bucket named `foo.bar` is directed to
`https://s3.amazonaws.com/foo.bar/`, and so the certificate will pass
validation.  The catch is that buckets in regions outside US
(N. Virginia) require the request to be sent to a region-specific URL.
The OSF doesn't currently track the bucket's region, so WB has to
look it up via the S3 API.  Once we have the region, we can update the
host, and all S3 actions should succeed.

v1: add conflict resolution logic to put() When creating a new folder or file in a directory, we may encounter
the situation where the new entity has the same name as another entity
of the opposite type in that directory.  Some providers allow this,
others do not, and others (Dropbox) behave weirdly.  We want to
provide consistent semantics for all providers.  When the provider
allows simultaneous names, each request should succeed with a 201
Created.  When they do not, the first request, regardless of kind,
should succeed, and the second should fail with a 409 Conflict.

Logic:

Note: this only applies to the case where the entity in the path
is a folder.  If it's a file, the collision isn't possible.

First we check if the target path already exists within the directory.
If so, we throw a 409, because we don't want to overwrite what's
already there.  If the user wants to update a file, they should do a
PUT against the file's endpoint, not the parent folder's.

If the target path does not exist, we check to see if the provider
allows files and folders with the same name to coexist.  If so,
there's no problem. If not, we check for the existance of an entity
with the same name of the opposite type.  If it exists, we throw a
409, otherwise proceed as usual.

One bit of weirdness is that Dropbox's exists() method returns [] if a
folder with the same name exists.  In this case, [] means True, but
python treats it as a falsey value.  To avoid this, we need to
explicitly test if the retval from exists() is a bool.

v1: add can_duplicate_names method to providers This method indicates whether a provider allows a file and a folder in

v1: split validators into pre- and post- validators We had been running our argument validators before checking that the
path given in the url was valid.  Since some of our validations test
argument/path combinations, we should move these until after weve
validated the path.  However, path validation always costs us at least
one provider API call, and some providers have strict rate limits.  To
avoid this, split the argument validators into pre- and
post-validators. Pre-validators are run before path validation and let
us reject bad queyr parameters, invalid header formattings, etc. early.
Post-validators are run after path validation and can accurately test
path/argument combinations.

freeze time to fix occasional failures in s3 tests The s3 request signature generation code relies on a time-to-live
parameter to calculate the signature.  It adds the ttl to the
result of time.time() to calculate the expiry time, then includes that
value as part of the signature payload.  If the time ticks over by a
second between when the mock url and request urls are generated, the
signatures will be different.  The signature is sent in a query param,
so the request mocker will fail to match the requests.

To fix, freeze time for all of s3.  The signature is required for all
requests, so freeze all request-making test classes.  I originally
tried wrapping the entire module in a freeze, but that failed.
Presumably, because the tests are being run asynchronously.  So
instead I decorated each test class individually.

s3: implement recursive delete A DELETE request against a non-empty folder path on Amazon S3 will not
delete the folder, because folders on S3 are inferred from the pathnames
of the file objects.  To fully delete a directory, we must delete each
object within it.  Amazon provides a bulk delete operation to make this
more efficient.

To run the bulk delete, we must first get the keys of all the objects
within the directory, then POST a request with an XML body containing
the keys to the delete endpoint.  S3 limits their object list
responses and bulk delete requests to 1000 entries.  In the event that
more than 1000 entries need to be deleted, we issue multiple requests
in 1000-key batches.

Fixes: [#OSF-4870]

github: avoid dataloss w/ folderops in large repos Folders (trees) in GitHub cannot be operated on directly, and must
instead be moved/renamed/deleted by manipulating the blob paths in the
master tree.  Unfortunately, GH truncates master tree listings for repos
with lots of files and does not provide a way to page through and
retrieve all entries. Any blobs omitted when updating the master tree
will be treated as deleted.  Therefore, it doesn't seem that we can
always safely perform certain folder ops on large repos, so instead we
throw a 501 Not Implemented with an explanatory message.

github: fix move to always remove src file When moving files from a non-root folder in github, the source file was
being left behind.  This was because the tree entry for the source
directory was left in the modified master tree, where it still contained
references to the old blob/tree.  The solution was to remove all tree
entries from the master tree and to allow github to infer the new tree
structure from the path names of the remaing blobs.

  the attribute partial set to True the status code will be set to 206,
  Partial Content, and the stream's response.content_range will be
  forwarded to the client under the Content-Range header.

Catch exception when the connection is closed during write_stream   If the client cancel a download mid way RequestHandler.write/Flush will
  raise a tornado.iostream.StreamClosedError. Swallow the exception in
  write_stream because its expected.

Merge pull request #54 from chrisseto/feature/tornado42 [Feature] tornado 4.2

Set tornado's max_body_size to 4.9 GB by default   max_buffer_size was previously being used to adjust acceptable body
  size, max_body_size is the more appropriate setting as it prevents 4GB
  of data being sent to non-streaming routes

Use sockets to create an upload stream   Previously a StreamReader was created and data was just being fed into
  it via feed_data. This caused entire files to be pulled into memory
  when the client's connection to waterbutler was faster than
  waterbutler's connection to the provider. Creating a StreamWriter,
  StreamReader pair gives access to the StreamWriter.drain method which
  will pause writing until the in memory buffer is below a certain
  threshold.

Upgrade to tornado 4.2   Due to increased compatablity with asyncio we no longer need any
  magical decoractors to translate futures for us. The
  tornado.gen.coroutine decorator now handles all the translation for
  us.
